a, Jeno, Arpad, Attila, Csaba.","Hungarian: variant of   Papp  , meaning ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’. This surname is also found in Romania, Slovakia, Croatia, and Serbia, and also among Rusyns (in Serbia and Croatia). See also   Pop   2 and   Popa  .","English: variant of   Pape   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Papp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Hungarian Laszlo, Zoltan, Geza, Istvan, Gabor, Miklos, Tibor, Arpad, Denes, Imre, Attila.","German (Bavaria, Tyrol): from Middle High German <i>pap</i> ‘baby food’, Dutch <i>pap</i> ‘porridge, pap’, hence perhaps a nickname denoting someone who had lost his teeth or subsisted on a meager diet.","Hungarian: from <i>pap</i> ‘priest (of the Catholic or Orthodox Church)’, probably an occupational name for someone in the service of a priest or a nickname for a pious person. This surname is also found in Romania and Slovakia, and also among Rusyns. Compare   Pap   and   Pop  ."]}]},{"name":"Einion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Tyrone): variant of   Moynihan  .","French: occupational name for a miner, from a diminutive of <i>minier</i> ‘miner’ (see   Minier  ). This surname is very rare in France; in North America it may thus (also) be an altered form of some other similar (like-sounding) French surname, such as   Mignon  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Moynihan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Patrick James, Donal, Eamon, Finbarr, Kieran, Niall.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Muimhneacháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Muimhneachán</i>’, a diminutive of the byname <i>Muimhneach</i> ‘Munsterman’, i.e. someone belonging to the province of Munster. In Mayo this surname has sometimes been translated into English as   Munster  . There has been some confusion with   Monaghan  ."]}]},{"name":"Owain","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Perhaps derived in the Roman period from the Latin name <i>Eugenius</i> (  see  <b>Eugene</b>   ); alternatively, possibly from an Old Celtic name meaning ‘born of Esos’. Esos (or Aesos) was a Celtic god known to have been the subject of a cult in ancient Gaul."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Owain ap Einion was born about 1174, in Denbighshire, Wales. She had at least 1 son with Owain ap Einion."},"et":{"about 1174–":"umbes 1174–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1202–Male":"1202–Surnud","1174–Female":"1174–Surnud","ABT    1202":"umbes 1202","1202":"1202","1174":"1174","about 1174":"umbes 1174","1170":"1170","of,Cynllaith,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1174–":"noin 1174–Kuollut","1170–Male":"1170–Kuollut","1202–Male":"1202–Kuollut","1174–Female":"1174–Kuollut","ABT    1202":"noin 1202","1202":"1202","1174":"1174","about 1174":"noin 1174","1170":"1170","of,Cynllaith,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1174–":"environ 1174–Décédée","1170–Male":"1170–Décédé","1202–Male":"1202–Décédé","1174–Female":"1174–Décédée","ABT    1202":"environ 1202","1202":"1202","1174":"1174","about 1174":"environ 1174","1170":"1170","of,Cynllaith,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Owain ap Einion est née environ 1174, à Denbighshire, Galles. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Owain ap Einion."},"de":{"about 1174–":"um 1174–Verstorben","1170–Male":"1170–Verstorben","1202–Male":"1202–Verstorben","1174–Female":"1174–Verstorben","ABT    1202":"um 1202","1202":"1202","1174":"1174","about 1174":"um 1174","1170":"1170","of,Cynllaith,Denbighshire,Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Owain ap Einion wurde um 1174 in Denbighshire, Wales geboren. 